author: adi1969

description.text:
Why do foot powder bottles come with baby powder tops? I don't want to cover my whole foot with powder, just between my toes!  
Here is my solution to this problem, a conical shape that fits snugly on top of the bottle and reduces the opening size to 8mm from about 25mm. Obeys the 45 degree rule for easy printing. Parametric and customizable in the scad file to fit your bottle and your toes.

Another way to store and feed your filament to your pet robot. :)  This is meant to allow a spool-less filament coil to be set on top and spin freely!  The key is to purchase filament which is properly coiled from the inside out.  Then you place on this device, be sure to begin feeding from the inside end.  As tension builds up, the filament will naturally uncoil.  This is meant for hands and worry free printing.  Uses the same principal found in NopHeads hanging basket design, except slightly more portable. :)
I should point out:  the coil will not support itself once the tie wraps are cut.  What i do when i get my filament is i tape the vacuum sealed bag in such a way that it conforms to the coil or toroidal shape.  Then i cut a hole in the center, which will be where the filament feeds out.  Then drop a desiccant of choice inside, and place in feeding accessory such as the sky hook or bDaisy design.

Needed to complete assembly: 8Mx45mm Bolt, 8M Nut, 8M washer, 2x 608 bearings, printed parts, and the laser cut disc.   See exploded diagram for assembly instructions.  The laser cut platform could be almost anything.  Balanced sturdy surface is needed.
bDaisy_spin and bDaisy_base are needed.  bDaisy_complete is just there for reference.

author: cfarr

description.text:
Updated: This cooling box is for TAZ3 3D printer, it uses a 50 mm muffin fan, it has three outlets: one outlet is for cooling extruded filament (good for PLA printing), one for keeping the extruder motor above it cool, and one for giving active cooling to the hot-end heat sink. The update is the addition of exhaust hole to the hot-end because I found that active cooling enables you to use more different brands of ABS filaments without which the Hobbed Bolt likes to dig into the filament too much.
You can close the holes you are not using with a scotch tape anytime...
You need two m3 6mm screws for mounting it on the right side of the hot end assembly, also it uses four Heat-set inserts (M2.5) for mounting the fan.

Scalable universal stand for anything on a reel. I use this to dispense PLA to my 3d printer but it could be used for anything on a reel. The reels I am using are recycled electrical cable reels and are 280mm diameter with a 98mm hole, these are very common in these parts and freely available. The whole construction is very much like the mendel prusa frame so is made from 8mm threaded rod, nuts and washers.
All the parts print in around an hour each and it is a good project to tidy up your print area and use up some scraps of filament.
This is the third version of this device.

Print out 2 ends, 4 feet and if you are using the reels I am using then at least two of the reels ends. The one in the photo takes three reels so used 6 reel ends.
For the one I have built you will need 6 x 180mm long threaded rods, 3 x 450mm long threaded rods, 20 M8 nuts and 18 washers.
The feet are printed with 7mm holes in the triangular frame holes and they need to be tapped out to 8mm metric (or equivalent UNC) thread.
After that it is just assemble it as it looks in the photo. To screw the threaded rods into the feet you may need to lock two nuts together and run them in with a spanner.
If you are using more than one reel as I have you should add two washers between each reel end on the top bar. The ends of the top bar are finished with a nut inside and outside the end top piece and tightened against each other leaving room for the reels to just spin freely.

comments.text: I've been thinking of making something like this, except wall mounted. Do you find it any easier or more difficult to feed filament to your machine from this than from a spool mounted to the printer?
comments.author: LiquidBeef

comments.text: I started with a spool on the top of the printer but I wanted to have several spools on the go and it is a bit of a strain on the printer with all that weight up high. It needed to be quite high to feed well. I also don't want to screw anything to the wall in the room I have my printer so this is the next best option but it does work extremely well and is quick to change filament etc.

author: Creative_Hacker

title: Bolt On Front Spool Bracket Original Hardware

description.text: I thought DeadCatDot's Bolt-On Front spool Bracket was great, but it doesn't work with the original screws that come on the Replicator 2. So I made one that does work with the original screws. I also widened the hole a little bit to work with bigger 27mm PVC pipe. You can use this with PVC pipe or with the friction fit spool holders I modeled. One for regular spools of varying sizes and one for Taulman Spools. I just printed it all at standard settings and it came out very sturdy. Just for fun I added a .thing file for Dualstrusion. It says INDOMITABLE in the center.
Print without support, I've included my own supports where needed.. It's pretty obvious which side goes down. Standard settings work well.
